"v./n.屠杀，屠宰 无 无 无 slaughter (n.)  c.1300, ""killing of a cattle or sheep for food, killing of a person,"" from a Scandinavian *slahtr, akin to Old Norse slatr ""a butchering, butcher meat,"" slatra ""to slaughter,"" slattr ""a mowing"" from Proto-Germanic *slukhtis, related to Old Norse sla ""to strike"" (see slay (v.)) + formative suffix (as in laugh/laughter). Meaning ""killing of a large number of persons in battle"" is attested from mid-14c. Old English had slieht ""stroke, slaughter, murder, death; animals for slaughter;"" as in sliehtswyn ""pig for killing."" slaughter (v.)  1530s, ""butcher an animal for market,"" from slaughter (n.). Meaning ""slay wantonly, ruthlessly, or in great numbers"" is from 1580s. Related: Slaughtered; slaughtering."
